# Story writing rules (house craft)

Use these whenever you write, expand, or revise stories in `src/data/stories/`. They override older notes that said to "state ages" on every character.

## 1. Dramatize — do not summarize plot

Do **not** leapfrog a beat with a one-sentence synopsis of what happened. If the moment matters (first discovery, first spanking, first betrayal, a ritual becoming weekly), write the scene: dialogue, sensory detail, a specific time/place, what the character does with their hands.

**Bad (summary / montage):**
> By spring the loophole had a schedule. She went to Brad twice a week and Noah waited in the car.

**Good (dramatize the turn):**
> The first Tuesday after spring break she texted *studying at Jack's* at 3:40. Noah parked under the maple with three unread books on the passenger seat. At 4:23 the upstairs blind went down. He catalogued the quiet the way he always did — and hated that he already knew which page of which book he would not turn.

**Also bad:** Opening with the entire premise dumped in one line
> Today the principal required Nikki to go to school completely naked because one sock was backwards.

**Better:** Arrive in the moment (locker, hallway, the order landing), then let cause and consequence unfold on the page.

When expanding existing stories: hunt for “by then / eventually / sessions became weekly / after that it was normal” and replace high-value ones with a single concrete scene. Do **not** pad every transitional phrase — only expand where a scene would actually earn its keep.

## 2. Ages — almost never, and never as a refrain

Most stories were opening with “X was twenty-eight, Y was thirty-four…” It reads like ID cards, not fiction.

**Default:** Establish adulthood with jobs, marriages, college, cohabiting, leases, dinner parties — **no numbers**.

**Allowed numeric ages (18–21 only)** when youth is load-bearing:
- High-school senior plots
- Living-with-parent / just-graduated ABDL or household discipline
- Freshman / explicit age-gap dynamics where the young age is the point

Even then: state it **once** at intro (excerpt + first paragraph is enough). Do **not** repeat “she was eighteen” every spanking, diaper change, or closing image. Parents and side characters almost never need ages.

**Bad:**
> Megan was twenty… She was twenty and secret… “You are twenty.” … twenty years old on the kitchen floor… twenty-year-old woman in the grocery aisle…

**Good:**
> Megan Shaw was twenty years old, worked closing at the Craft Barn, and had been careful about her hamper for six months.
> Later: “Adult daughter. Employed. Living under my roof.”

**Bad (adult filler):**
> Jordan Hale was twenty-six… Melissa Ruiz was twenty-four…
> Rachel was thirty-two… James was thirty-four… Simone was forty-one…

**Good:** Drop the numbers; keep jobs, temperament, and relationship length.

Never write or imply minors. “Boy” / “girl” in kink = adult. Never compare ageplay characters to a child age (“like an 8-year-old”).

## 3. No consent theatre

The site waiver already covers consenting adults. CNC and reluctant heat are welcome. Do **not** insert:

- Safewords, traffic lights (green / yellow / red)
- Mid-scene “Color?” / “Still okay?” / “You can stop this”
- Negotiation transcripts that break erotic momentum
- Disclaimers that the characters “discussed boundaries earlier” unless that *is* the scene

Show power, fear, want, and aftermath. Do not lecture the reader that everyone consented.

## 4. Names — sparse, never Aaron/Eric

Do **not** name characters **Aaron** or **Eric** (any spelling).

Prefer **not** naming characters at all unless a name does real story work (a Domme brand, a collar plate, a text contact, a public introduction). Default to he/she, girlfriend, husband, Sir, Mommy, the Domme, the bull. If you use a name, one is usually enough — do not roll-call every side character.

**Bad:** Opening with full names and ages for everyone in the room.  
**Good:** “His girlfriend sent the video at 9:14. On screen, the other man’s belt buckle filled the frame before his face did.”

## 5. Excerpts — lead with the sexual beat

The catalog `excerpt` is a **hook**, not a spoiler-safe premise blurb. Soft setup-only summaries underperform.

**Must include** one or more concrete sexual elements from the story: acts, implements, body parts, pricing for orgasm/unlock, positions, fluids, denial, chastity, spanking counts, etc.

**Must not** stop at logistics alone (cleared history, AirPlay, hamper, wine poured, Discord mute, shared wallet) without naming what the sex/kink actually is.

**Shape:** 1–2 punchy sentences. Specific nouns beat vague teasing. A choice / receipt / countdown / “thank you” line is fine if it carries heat.

**Bad (setup only):**
> She swore it was just a drinking game. Then she moved the goalposts, smiled, and asked which boy was brave enough to clean up the other.

**Good (sexual beat first):**
> Just a drinking game, she swore. Then both boys were bare on her carpet, Avery milking them onto their own stomachs — and asking which one was brave enough to lick the other clean, mouth only, swallow what you collect.

**Bad:**
> Elise had dinner with Marcus. Cole paid the Uber, the wine, the hotel — locked in pink plastic at home, watching the charges land like love notes.

**Good:**
> Locked in pink plastic at home, Cole paid Uber, wine, hotel — then listened while Elise choked on Marcus and came on the cock his Visa rented the room for. When she got home, she put him on his knees and made him tongue-clean the receipt.

When writing or revising any story: draft the excerpt **after** the filthy climax of the piece is clear, and audit it the same way — if you could swap brands and still not know the kink, rewrite.

**ABDL phrasing:** say **in the diaper position** (on the back, legs up). Prefer “get in the diaper position” / “into the diaper position.” Do **not** write “strip for diaper position” — stripping and the position are separate steps.

## 6. Boys/men in panties — emasculation and humiliation, not “soft clothes”

When a **boy or man** wears panties (forced, volunteered, cuckold waiting clothes, sissy kit, cage cover, etc.), the erotic point is **emasculation / humiliation** — private shame, being dressed as less of a man, girl's underwear that marks him as the one who waits or serves. Frame it that way.

This does **not** apply to women/girls wearing their own panties as ordinary clothing or sexual costume.

**Do:**
- Emphasize wrongness, girl's fabric, the bow as a punchline, being smaller than the men who get her, waiting in underwear that unmans him
- Let each story use its own vocabulary (girl's underwear, sissy, pretty as a slur/command, locked boy in girl's cotton, taking him down a size). Do **not** paste the same stock phrase into every story
- Keep “pretty,” “cute,” “good girl,” “soft boy” only when they **cut** — mockery, branding, sing-song cruelty — not when they sand the edges off the shame

**Don't:**
- Call male panties “soft clothes,” “the soft look,” or frame them mainly as care/comfort
- Prefer “more like care than humiliation” or “keeping you soft” as the thesis of the panties
- Soften the beat into aftercare aesthetics when the scene's job is to shrink him

**Bad:**
> Sometimes soft clothes for him — panties — so he feels cared for while she dates.
> Pink panties over the cage if you want the soft look.

**Good:**
> Sometimes girl's underwear for him — panties — so the waiting itself takes the man out of him.
> Pink panties over the cage so he can see what you wear for me.
> Locked boy in girl's cotton. Cute and useless.

When revising older stories: hunt male-panty beats for care/soft framing and re-aim them at shame/emasculation in that story's voice.

## 7. Sentence length — no fragment spam

Do **not** fill stories with stacks of tiny standalone sentences (1–4 words) that only describe, list, or hedge. Weak little quips should be **deleted** or rewritten as a **full natural sentence** with verbs and ordinary flow.

**Do not** “fix” fragments by gluing them with commas or em-dashes into crumb chains (`musk, skin, man` / `tall, easy, sales` / `— chemical, floral, wrong —`). That is still fragment spam — just punctuated differently. Swapping commas for a string of “and…and…and” is also not enough if the line is still a crumb list.

**Short sentences are allowed** when they earn their keep:
- A real bombshell / erotic punch (“We fucked. Twice.” / “I came.” / “She was not safe.”)
- Sparse Domme/command voice, used sparingly
- Occasional dialogue that matches a specific personality (a blunt Domme; a rattled one-word reply) — **not** every character, and not as their default cadence
- Text-message / timestamp lines
- Isolated action beats (“He swallowed.”) when not stacked in threes
- Intentional sound/ritual beats (`tap, tap, tap` / counting) when that *is* the point

**Bad (standalone crumbs):**
> "I think Connor saw my panties when I bent over. White ones. Ordinary. The reading said…"
> Musk. Skin. Man. The inhale punched through him.
> Marcus. Tall. Easy. Sales.

**Also bad (glued crumbs — not a fix):**
> His nose sank into the cleft — musk, skin, man — and the inhale punched through him.
> Marcus was tall, easy, sales — the kind of man who…
> She stripped — shoes, jeans, shirt, bra, panties last…
> Soap flooded his tongue — chemical, floral, wrong.

**Good (delete the quip, or write a real sentence):**
> "I think Connor saw my panties when I bent over, the ordinary white ones. The reading said…"
> The smell hit him first, musk and skin and something unmistakably male, and the inhale punched through him so hard his eyes watered.
> Marcus was a tall sales guy who laughed with his whole chest and never checked his phone under the table.
> She took off her shoes and jeans, then her shirt and bra, and left the panties for last, folding each piece once out of habit.
> Soap flooded his tongue with a chemical floral taste that felt wrong in every way food was right.
> We fucked. Twice. *(bombshell — keep)*

**Heuristic when editing:** if you see two or more tiny descriptive crumbs in a row (periods **or** commas/dashes), either cut them or turn the idea into one ordinary flowing sentence. Do not leave `word, word, word` stacks as style.

## 8. No therapy-speak euphemism for desire

Do **not** abstract kink, jealousy, or arousal into soft clinical / therapeutic phrases. Characters can avoid porn slang; they should still sound personal and ordinary, not like a worksheet. Vague therapy talk is a turn-off because readers cannot tell what is actually happening.

**Bad (floaty therapy / worksheet abstractions):**
> for your feeling / understand your feeling / try the feeling / the right shape
> sit with it / sit with the unread feeling / sit with the smell
> emotional labor / even the energy out / mature framework / self-care *(when used as kink cover)*
> hides her need / the need / my need used your regret
> a check-in *(when it means a Domme call or soap follow-up — say what it is)*
> the dynamic / permission practice / version of you *(when floaty)*
> billed by the feeling / tip the feeling / buying the feeling of being chosen

**Good (personal, concrete):**
> because you want this / this thing you like / try what you asked for
> keep tasting it / keep smelling him on me / sit in the unread silence you bought
> that's a lot of work for him with no thank-you / even things out / just me working on myself
> sneaks off to get fucked / wanting it / I used your regret as a door
> Sunday call / quick video / follow-up / another session
> the Daddy arrangement / saying yes to small attention / the little waiting boyfriend I'm keeping
> billed for the tease / tip for that / paying to feel chosen by a girl who sells that to everyone
> your ears went red / your stomach dropped / you got hard when I told you

Soft vocabulary ≠ vague psychology. Prefer “what you want,” “your thing,” “because you asked,” named acts, and body reactions over “your feeling,” “the need,” “process,” “space,” “check-in,” “framework,” or “shape” talk about desire.

Applies to **all** authors and stories, including cute/inquisitive girlfriends and Dommes who speak gently. Character satire of wellness jargon is fine only when the line still makes the act clear.

## 9. Chapters (optional)

Most stories are single-chapter (`pages` only). Multi-chapter stories:

- Keep one catalog entry (browse / author / home). Never register extra chapters as separate stories.
- Set `firstChapterName` + `firstChapterSummary` for the opening `pages` body, plus `chapters: [{ name, summary, pages }, …]` for the rest.
- **Every chapter has a name and a short summary.** Summaries are chapter-specific blurbs for the story-page dropdown — **not** a copy of the catalog `excerpt`.
- The story page shows a chapter dropdown (name only) below tags and above page pagination; minutes and that chapter's summary appear directly under the dropdown for the selected chapter.
- Read time on cards and the story kicker is the **sum** of all chapters.
- Each chapter should still meet the 5-minute minimum on its own when practical.

## 10. Length and registration (unchanged)

- Minimum **5-minute** read: ≥ **1150** words of body text at **230 WPM** (`node scripts/count-words.mjs` / `getReadingMinutes`). No `UNDER 5 MIN`. Multi-chapter: count all chapters; prefer each chapter ≥5 min.
- Match `Story` shape in `src/types.ts`; register in `src/data/stories/index.ts`.
- Follow the selected author’s `writingStyle` in `src/data/authors.ts`, except where this rule file conflicts (ages, consent theatre, banned names, no plot-summary, sexual excerpts, male panties as emasculation/humiliation, fragment spam, no therapy-speak desire) — **this file wins**.

## 11. Quick checklist before shipping a new story

- [ ] Opens in a scene, not a premise dump
- [ ] Excerpt leads with concrete sexual beats (not logistics-only setup)
- [ ] Multi-chapter: every chapter named + summarized; still one catalog entry
- [ ] No adult age numbers used as character IDs
- [ ] If 18–21 appears, it appears once for a plot reason — not as a refrain
- [ ] No safewords / traffic lights / “still okay?”
- [ ] No characters named Aaron or Eric
- [ ] If a boy/man wears panties: framed as emasculation/humiliation (not “soft clothes” / care) — see §6
- [ ] No fragment spam: weak 1–4 word stacks deleted or rewritten as full sentences — see §7
- [ ] No therapy-speak for desire (“your feeling,” “right shape,” etc.) — see §8
- [ ] ≥1150 words; `npm run count-words` clean; builds
